# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-la-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The **Allard J2** is a sports roadster that was made by Allard.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The J2 was mainly intended for the American market.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Since 1981, replicas of the later J2X have been manufactured by a succession of companies in Canada, whilst a continuation of the original models is also now being produced in the UK.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The standard J2 engine in Britain was the 3.6 L flathead V8 engine from the Ford Pilot, delivering 85 hp.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] A 4.4 L Mercury V8, delivering 110 hp was also available.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] American enthusiasts modified their cars by fitting an Oldsmobile, Chrysler, or Cadillac V8.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] J2s exported to the United States were shipped without engines.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Then, an engine of the buyer's choice installed locally.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] This proved to be very successful, and the use of American components made it very easy to find parts for Allard's customers.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The front suspension was a swing axle with coil springs while the rear had a De Dion tube system with coil springs, inboard brakes and a quick-change differential.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Ninety J2s were built between 1950 and 1951.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] In 1952 Allard replaced the J2 with the J2X.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] In an attempt to improve handling, the J2X had redesigned front suspension arrangement that allowed its engine to be positioned about 18 centimetres (7.1 in) further forward than the J2 engine had been.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] This did a few things beside improving the weight distribution: it gave the driver more leg room, and also facilitated easy identification between the two models J2 and J2X ("X" for extended).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The longer nose sticks out beyond the front wheels (unlike the J2 where the nose stops even with the front of the front tires) and this is the easiest way to differentiate between the two.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The J2X also had side access panels for the engine and most models came with a standardized wide flat hood scoop, unlike the J2s where each one has a different custom built hood arrangement.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Also offered as an option was a differential with quick-change ratios, and a larger fuel tank.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Its 170 hp engine could propel the car from 0-60 in 10 seconds and gave the J2X a top speed of 111.6 mph.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The interior remained simple with only a few gauges.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] For the 1952 Le Mans 24-hours race, new rule changes required fully enclosed wheels.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Allard quickly developed new, barchetta-style bodywork to meet the regulations and called the resulting car the J2X Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Between nine and fourteen such cars were built, fitted with various American V8 engines as per Allard practice.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] While one of the fastest Allards ever, the design was past its time and was never fully competitive in the period.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Two cars competed in the 1952 Le Mans, but both cars retired in the fifteenth hour.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The best results were a second place in a 1952 Formula Libre race at Snetterton, and a handful of victories in American SCCA races.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Beginning their work in 1981, two Canadian enthusiasts in Ontario revived the J2X concept as the **J2X2**.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Mel Stein and Arnold Korne, who owned the coachbuilding company A.H.A.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Manufacturing Company Limited, characterized their effort as a revival rather than a recreation, although a number of changes were carried out compared to the original design.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The wheels on the J2X2 are considerably smaller than period pieces, the bodywork is in a mix of aluminium and fibreglass, the steering rack was swapped to a rack and pinion unit, while the front suspension was changed to a more conventional wishbone design.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The brakes were power assisted, and the front drums were replaced by discs.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] It was available in kit form, or fully built.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The fully built version received Chrysler's 5.2-liter V8 engine and a four-speed manual gearbox, although an automatic unit was available.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The car also received rudimentary protection from the elements in the form of loose side windows and a simple hood.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] There was also a competition version without the intrusion of modern bumpers and with a shorter windscreen.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] A right-hand drive version was available for British buyers.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Allard's son Alan fully approved of the car, even taking on the European distribution.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Roger P Allard's, Allard Motor Works, located in Montreal, Quebec, Canada, builds what their website calls "a modern hand-crafted version of the famed British competition roadster that stirred crowds in Europe and North America", known as the J2X MkII.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] While looking similar to the original J2X, its glass-fibre body is dimensionally dissimilar and the chassis and drive-train are entirely different.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Aside from the badges, few if any parts are transferable between this and a Sydney Allard built car.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Roger Allard and Allard Motor Works are not connected or related to the original Allard company or Sydney Allard in London England.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The 'J2X MKII' is a fibreglass bodied lookalike in the spirit of the original 1951-1954 J2X.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Allard engineers hand built the car at a rate of 100 per year, while keeping it in compliance with modern standards for automotive safety.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The new J2X has a GM RAM Jet V8 engine that produces about 350 hp and 400 lb/ft of torque.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Other engine choices include a 600-hp 6.1-liter Hemi, a Chevrolet 350, Cadillac Northstar or Ford 351.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The 0-60 time is 4.5 seconds and the quarter mile time is 12 seconds at 110 mph.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Power is transferred through a Tremec TKO five-speed manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] In 2012, a new Allard company, Allard Sports Cars, was formed by Lloyd Allard, and announced they would be making new versions of the J2X.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Unlike the Canadian versions, which are new designs based on the original, the British cars are continuations of the original designs.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] The company officially reopened its business and began production in September 2018.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] In 1951, Bill Pollack drove an Allard J2 with a Cadillac V8 to victory at the Pebble Beach Road Race.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Thus, it headlined less often in major international races and of 199 documented major race starts in the 9 years between 1952 and 1960, J2X's garnered 12 first-place finishes; 11 seconds; 17 thirds; 14 fourths; and 10 fifth places.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/allard-j2-original] Overall, both cars epitomize the pinnacle of the Allard Motor Company and are generally the car design thought of when the name Allard is mentioned.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] The **automotive industry** comprises a wide range of companies and organisations involved in the design, development, manufacturing, marketing, selling, repairing, and modification of motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] It is one of the world's largest industries by revenue with global automotive market at ~$2.75 trillion in 2025.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] The word *automotive* comes from the Greek *autos* (self), and Latin *motivus* (of motion), referring to any form of self-powered vehicle.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] This term, as proposed by Elmer Sperry (1860–1930), first came into use to describe automobiles in 1898.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] The automotive industry began in the 1860s with hundreds of manufacturers pioneering the horseless carriage.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Early car manufacturing involved manual assembly by a human worker.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] The process evolved from engineers working on a stationary car to a conveyor belt system where the car passed through multiple stations of more specialised engineers.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] In the 1960s, robotic equipment was introduced, and most cars are now mainly assembled by automated machinery.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] For many decades, the United States led the world in total automobile production, with the U.S.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Big Three General Motors, Ford Motor Company, and Chrysler being the world's three largest auto manufacturers for a time, and G.M. and Ford remaining the two largest until the mid-2000s.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] In 1929, before the Great Depression, the world had 32,028,500 automobiles in use, of which the U.S. automobile enterprises produced more than 90%.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] At that time, the U.S. had one car per 4.87 persons.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] After 1945, the U.S. produced around three-quarters of the world's auto production.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] In 1980, the U.S. was overtaken by Japan and then became a world leader again in 1994.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Japan narrowly passed the U.S. in production during 2006 and 2007, and in 2008 also China, which in 2009 took the top spot (from Japan) with 13.8 million units, although the U.S. surpassed Japan in 2011, to become the second-largest automobile industry.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] In 2024, China produced more than 31 million vehicles in a year, after breaking 30 million in 2023, reaching 29 million for the first time in 2017 and 28 million the year before.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] In 2024, China produced the most passenger cars in the world, with Japan, India, Germany, and South Korea trailing.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] This was achieved by Chinese car companies signing joint ventures with foreign manufacturers.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] From 1970 (140 models) to 1998 (260 models) to 2012 (684 models), the number of automobile models in the U.S. has grown nearly twofold.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Safety is a state that implies being protected from any risk, danger, damage, or cause of injury.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] In the automotive industry, safety means that users, operators, or manufacturers do not face any risk or danger coming from the motor vehicle or its spare parts.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Safety for the automobiles themselves implies that there is no risk of damage.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Safety in the automotive industry is particularly important and therefore highly regulated.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Automobiles and other motor vehicles have to comply with a certain number of regulations, whether local or international, in order to be accepted on the market.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] The standard ISO 26262, is considered one of the best practice frameworks for achieving automotive functional safety.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] In case of safety issues, danger, product defect, or faulty procedure during the manufacturing of the motor vehicle, the maker can request to return either a batch or the entire production run.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] This procedure is called product recall.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Product recalls happen in every industry and can be production-related or stem from raw materials.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Product and operation tests and inspections at different stages of the value chain are made to avoid these product recalls by ensuring end-user security and safety and compliance with the automotive industry requirements.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] However, the automotive industry is still particularly concerned about product recalls, which cause considerable financial consequences.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] In 2007, there were about 806 million cars and light trucks on the road, consuming over 980 billion litres (980,000,000 m3) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] The automobile is a primary mode of transportation for many developed economies.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] The Detroit branch of Boston Consulting Group predicted that, by 2014, one-third of world demand would be in the four BRIC markets (Brazil, Russia, India, and China).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Meanwhile, in developed countries, the automotive industry has slowed.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] It is also expected that this trend will continue, especially as the younger generations of people (in highly urbanised countries) no longer want to own a car, and prefer other modes of transport.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Other potentially powerful automotive markets are Iran and Indonesia.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Emerging automobile markets already buy more cars than established markets.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Power study, emerging markets accounted for 51 percent of the global light-vehicle sales in 2010.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] The study, performed in 2010 expected this trend to accelerate.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] However, more recent reports (2012) confirmed the opposite; namely that the automotive industry was slowing down even in BRIC countries.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] In the United States, vehicle sales peaked in 2000, at 17.8 million units.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] In July 2021, the European Commission released its "Fit for 55" legislation package, which contains important guidelines for the future of the automotive industry; all new cars on the European market must be zero-emission vehicles from 2035.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] The governments of 24 developed countries and a group of major car manufacturers including GM, Ford, Volvo, BYD Auto, Jaguar Land Rover and Mercedes-Benz committed to "work towards all sales of new cars and vans being zero emission globally by 2040, and by no later than 2035 in leading markets".
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Major car manufacturing nations like the United States, Germany, China, Japan and South Korea, as well as Volkswagen, Toyota, Peugeot, Honda, Nissan and Hyundai, did not pledge.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] The global automotive industry is a major consumer of water.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Some estimates surpass 180,000 L (39,000 imp gal) of water per car manufactured, depending on whether tyre production is included.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Production processes that use a significant volume of water include surface treatment, painting, coating, washing, cooling, air-conditioning, and boilers, not counting component manufacturing.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Paintshop operations consume especially large amounts of water because equipment running on water-based products must also be cleaned with water.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] In 2022, Tesla's Gigafactory Berlin-Brandenburg ran into legal challenges due to droughts and falling groundwater levels in the region.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Brandenburg's Economy Minister Joerg Steinbach said that while water supply was sufficient during the first stage, more would be needed once Tesla expands the site.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] The factory would nearly double the water consumption in the Gruenheide area, with 1.4 million cubic meters being contracted from local authorities per year — enough for a city of around 40,000 people.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Steinbach said that the authorities would like to drill for more water there and outsource any additional supply if necessary.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] : US had produced more than 80% of motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] : India overtakes Germany to become 4th largest automobile producer.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] The OICA counts over 50 countries that assemble, manufacture, or disseminate automobiles.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Of those, only 15 countries (**boldfaced** in the list below) currently possess the capability to design original production automobiles from the ground up, and 17 countries (listed below) have at least one million produced vehicles a year (as of 2023).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] All ten remained as the ten largest car makers by sales until the merger between Fiat-Chrysler and the PSA Group in early 2021; only Renault was degraded to 11th place, in 2022, when being surpassed by both BMW (which became the 10th largest in 2021) and Chang'an.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] The eighteen largest as of 2013 have remained in the top 20 as of 2017, except Mitsubishi which fell out of top 20 in 2016, while Geely fell out of the top 20 in 2014 and 2015 but re-entered it in 2016.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Mercedes-Benz Group held a combined 6.2% stake in the Renault–Nissan–Mitsubishi Alliance, and the Renault-Nissan-Mitsubishi Alliance also held a combined 6.2% stake in Mercedes-Benz Group until 2021.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] Until 2022, China required foreign automotive firms to form joint ventures in order to access their market.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/automotive-industry] The policy led to quality improvement across the industry.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] A **barrel** or **cask** is a hollow cylindrical container with a bulging center, longer than it is wide.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] They are traditionally made of wooden staves and bound by wooden or metal hoops.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The word **vat** is often used for large containers for liquids, usually alcoholic beverages; a small barrel or cask is known as a keg.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Barrels have a variety of uses, including storage of liquids such as water, oil, and alcohol.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] They are also employed to hold maturing beverages such as wine, cognac, armagnac, sherry, port, whiskey, beer, arrack, and sake.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Other commodities once stored in wooden casks include gunpowder, meat, fish, paint, honey, nails, and tallow.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Modern wooden barrels for wine-making are made of English oak (*Quercus robur*), white oak (*Quercus petraea*), American white oak (*Quercus alba*), more exotic is mizunara oak (*Quercus crispula*), and recently Oregon oak (*Quercus garryana*) has been used.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Someone who makes traditional wooden barrels is called a cooper.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Today, barrels and casks can also be made of aluminum, stainless steel, and different types of plastic, such as HDPE.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Early casks were bound with wooden hoops and in the 19th century these were gradually replaced by metal hoops that were stronger, more durable and took up less space.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] An Egyptian wall-painting in the tomb of Hesy-Ra, dating to 2600 BC, shows a wooden tub used to measure wheat and constructed of staves bound together with wooden hoops.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Another Egyptian tomb painting dating to 1900 BC shows a cooper and tubs made of staves in use at the grape harvest.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] 425 BC) allegedly reports the use of "palm-wood casks" in ancient Babylon, but some modern scholarship disputes this interpretation.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] In Europe, buckets and casks dating to 200 BC have been found preserved in the mud of lake villages.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] A lake village near Glastonbury dating to the late Iron Age has yielded one complete tub and a number of wooden staves.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The Roman historian Pliny the Elder (died 79 AD) reported that cooperage in Europe originated with the Gauls in Alpine villages who stored their beverages in wooden casks bound with hoops.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Pliny identified three different types of coopers: ordinary coopers, wine coopers and coopers who made large casks.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Large casks contain more and bigger staves and are correspondingly more difficult to assemble.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Roman coopers tended to be independent tradesmen, passing their skills on to their sons.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] 24 AD) recorded that wooden *pithoi* (barrels or wine-jars) were lined with pitch to stop leakage and preserve the wine.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Barrels were sometimes used for military purposes.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Julius Caesar (100 to 44 BC) used catapults to hurl burning barrels of tar into besieged towns to start fires.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The Romans also used empty barrels to make pontoon bridges to cross rivers.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Empty casks were used to line the walls of shallow wells from at least Roman times.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Such casks were found in 1897 during archaeological excavations of Roman Silchester in Britain.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] They were made of Pyrenean silver fir and the staves were 38 mm (1.5 in) thick and featured grooves where the heads fitted.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] They had Roman numerals scratched on the surface of each stave to help with re-assembly.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] In Anglo-Saxon Britain, wooden barrels were used to store ale, butter, honey and mead.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Drinking-containers were also made from small staves of oak, yew or pine.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] These items required considerable craftsmanship to hold liquids and might be bound with finely-worked precious metals.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] They were highly valued items and were sometimes buried with the dead as grave goods.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] In medieval and early modern Northern Europe, wooden casks were the primary container for wet and dry cargoes carried by ships, akin to the ceramic amphora transport jars used from antiquity in the Mediterranean region.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Wooden barrels carried foodstuffs such as fish, beer, honey, butter, apples, raisins, nuts, malt, beans, peas, grain, barley, and oats.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Gunpowder, iron, tar, coals, potash, lime, vinegar, and candles were transported in barrels; and no doubt much more.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] As with amphoras, different production centers applied various volumetric standards to the casks.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] This was enforced in some places by using sophisticated methods of gauging the casks, and then certifying the standard by municipal seals.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] In other places, such as the Hanseatic League town of Rostock, barrel volume was determined by the number of dressed and salted herring packed into them.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Some Hanse traders enforced their standards by destroying casks that did not conform.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Standardized cask volume was therefore an indicator of political economy.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] An "ageing barrel" is used to age wine; distilled spirits such as whiskey, brandy, or rum; beer; tabasco sauce; or (in smaller sizes) traditional balsamic vinegar.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] When a wine or spirit ages in a barrel, small amounts of oxygen are introduced as the barrel lets some air in (compare to microoxygenation where oxygen is deliberately added).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Oxygen enters a barrel when water or alcohol is lost due to evaporation, a portion known as the "angels' share".
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] In an environment with 100% relative humidity, very little water evaporates and so most of the loss is alcohol, a useful trick if one has a wine with very high proof.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Most beverages are topped up from other barrels to prevent significant oxidation, although others such as vin jaune and sherry are not.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Beverages aged in wooden barrels take on some of the compounds in the barrel, such as vanillin and wood tannins.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The presence of these compounds depends on many factors, including the place of origin, how the staves were cut and dried, and the degree of "toast" applied during manufacture.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Barrels used for aging are typically made of French or American oak, but chestnut and redwood are also used.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Some Asian beverages (e.g., Japanese sake) use Japanese cedar, which imparts an unusual, minty-piney flavor.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] In Peru and Chile, a grape distillate named *pisco* is either aged in oak or in earthenware.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Some wines are fermented "on barrel", as opposed to in a neutral container like steel or wine-grade HDPE (high-density polyethylene) tanks.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Wine can also be fermented in large wooden tanks, which—when open to the atmosphere—are called "open-tops".
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Other wooden cooperage for storing wine or spirits range from smaller barriques to huge casks, with either elliptical or round heads.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The tastes yielded by French and American species of oak are slightly different, with French oak being subtler, while American oak gives stronger aromas.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] To retain the desired measure of oak influence, a winery will replace a certain percentage of its barrels every year, although this can vary from 5 to 100%.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Some winemakers use "200% new oak", where the wine is put into new oak barrels twice during the aging process.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Bulk wines are sometimes more cheaply flavored by soaking in oak chips or added commercial oak flavoring instead of being aged in a barrel because of the much lower cost.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Sherry is stored in 600-litre (130 imp gal; 160 US gal) casks made of North American oak, which is slightly more porous than French or Spanish oak.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The casks, or butts, are filled five-sixths full, leaving "the space of two fists" empty at the top to allow flor to develop on top of the wine.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Sherry is also commonly swapped between barrels of different ages, a process that is known as *solera*.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Laws in several jurisdictions require that whiskey be aged in wooden barrels.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The law in the United States requires that "straight whiskey" (with the exception of corn whiskey) must be stored for at least two years in new, charred oak containers.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Other forms of whiskey aged in used barrels cannot be called "straight".
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] International laws require any whisky bearing the label "Scotch" to be distilled and matured in Scotland for a minimum of three years and one day in oak casks.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] By Canadian law, Canadian whiskies must "be aged in small wood for not less than three years", and "small wood" is defined as a wood barrel not exceeding 700 litres (150 imp gal; 180 US gal) capacity.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Since US law requires the use of new barrels for several popular types of whiskey, which is not typically considered necessary elsewhere, whiskey made elsewhere is usually aged in used barrels that previously contained American whiskey (usually bourbon whiskey).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The typical bourbon barrel is 53 US gallons (200 L; 44 imp gal) in size, which is thus the *de facto* standard whiskey barrel size worldwide.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Some distillers transfer their whiskey into different barrels to "finish" or add qualities to the final product.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] These finishing barrels frequently aged a different spirit (such as rum) or wine.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Other distillers, particularly those producing Scotch, often disassemble five used bourbon barrels and reassemble them into four casks with different barrel ends for aging Scotch, creating a type of cask referred to as a hogshead.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Maturing is very important for a good brandy, which is typically aged in oak casks.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The wood used for those barrels is selected because of its ability to transfer certain aromas to the spirit.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Cognac is aged only in oak casks made from wood from the Forest of Tronçais and more often from the Limousin forests.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Some types of tequila are aged in oak barrels to mellow its flavor.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] "Reposado" tequila is aged for a period of two months to one year, "Añejo" tequila is aged for up to three years, and "Extra Añejo" tequila is aged for at least three years.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Like with other spirits, longer aging results in a more pronounced flavor.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Beers are sometimes aged in barrels which were previously used for maturing wines or spirits.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] This is most common in darker beers such as stout, which is sometimes aged in oak barrels identical to those used for whiskey.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Whisky distiller Jameson notably purchases barrels used by Franciscan Well brewery for their Shandon Stout to produce a whisky branded as "Jameson Caskmates".
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Cask ale is aged in the barrel (usually steel) for a short time before serving.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Extensive barrel aging is required of many sour beers.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Traditional balsamic vinegar is aged in a series of wooden barrels.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The pepper mash used to make Tabasco sauce is aged for three years in previously used oak whiskey barrels since its invention in 1868.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Vernors ginger ale is marketed as having a "barrel-aged" flavor, and the syrup used to produce the beverage was originally aged in oak barrels when first manufactured in the 19th century.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Whether the syrup continues to be aged in oak is unclear.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] "Angels' share" is a term for the portion (share) of a wine or distilled spirit's volume that is lost to evaporation during aging in oak barrels.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The ambient humidity tends to affect the composition of this share.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Drier conditions tend to make the barrels evaporate more water, strengthening the spirit.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] However, in higher humidities, more alcohol than water will evaporate, therefore reducing the alcoholic strength of the product.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] This alcoholic evaporate encourages the growth of a darkly colored fungus, the angels' share fungus, *Baudoinia compniacensis*, which tends to appear on the exterior surfaces of most things in the immediate area.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Water barrels are often used to collect the rainwater from dwellings (so that it may be used for irrigation or other purposes).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] This usage, known as rainwater harvesting, requires (besides a large rainwater barrel or water butt) adequate (waterproof) roof-covering and an adequate rain pipe.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Wooden casks of various sizes were used to store whale oil on ships in the age of sail.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Its viscous nature made sperm whale oil a particularly difficult substance to contain in staved containers.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Oil coopers were probably the most skilled coopers in pre-industrial cooperage.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Olive oil, seed oils and other organic oils were also placed in wooden casks for storage or transport.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Wooden casks were also used to store mineral oil.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The standard size barrel of crude oil or other petroleum product (abbreviated bbl) is 42 US gallons (35.0 imp gal; 159.0 L).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] This measurement originated in the early Pennsylvania oil fields, and permitted both British and American merchants to refer to the same unit, based on the old English wine measure, the tierce.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Earlier, another size of whiskey barrel was the most common size; this was the 40 US gallons (33.3 imp gal; 151.4 L) barrel for proof spirits, which was of the same volume as five US bushels.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] However, by 1866, the oil barrel was standardized at 42 US gallons.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Oil has not been shipped in barrels since the introduction of oil tankers, but the 42 US gallon size is still used as a unit of measurement for pricing and tax and regulatory codes.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Each barrel is refined into about 20 US gallons (17 imp gal; 76 L) of gasoline, the rest becoming other products such as jet fuel and heating oil, using fractional distillation.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Barrels have a convex shape and bulge at their center, called bilge.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] This facilitates rolling a well-built wooden barrel on its side and allows the roller to change directions with little friction, compared to a cylinder.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] It also helps to distribute stress evenly in the material by making the container more curved.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Barrels have reinforced edges to enable safe displacement by rolling them at an angle (in addition to rolling on their sides as described).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Casks used for ale or beer have shives and keystones in their openings.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Before serving the beer, a spile is hammered into the shive and a tap into the keystone.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The wooden parts that make up a barrel are called **staves**, the top and bottom are both called **heads** or **headers**, and the rings that hold the staves together are called **hoops**.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] These are usually made of galvanized iron, though historically they were made of flexible bits of wood called withies.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] While wooden hoops could require barrels to be "fully hooped", with hoops stacked tightly together along the entire top and bottom third of a barrel, iron-hooped barrels only require a few hoops on each end.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Wine barrels typically come in two hoop configurations.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] An American barrel features six hoops, from top to center: **head-** or **chime hoop**, **quarter hoop** and **bilge hoop** (times two), while a French barrel features eight, including a so-called **French hoop**, located between the quarter- and bilge hoops (see "wine barrel parts" illustration).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The opening at the center of a barrel is called a bunghole and the stopper used to seal it is a bung.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The latter is generally made of white silicone.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] A barrel is one of several units of volume, with dry barrels, fluid barrels (UK beer barrel, US beer barrel), oil barrel, etc.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The volume of some barrel units is double others, with various volumes in the range of about 100–200 litres (22–44 imp gal; 26–53 US gal).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The pre-1824 wine gallon continues to be used in the US, with 231 cubic inches being the standard gallon for liquids.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] In Britain and its colonies, the wine gallon was replaced by the imperial gallon in 1826.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The tierce later became the petrol barrel.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The tun was originally 256 gallons, which explains the origin of the quarter, 8 bushels or 64 (wine) gallons.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Although it is common to refer to draught beer containers of any size as barrels, in the UK this is strictly correct only if the container holds 36 imperial gallons.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The terms "keg" and "cask" refer to containers of any size, the distinction being that kegs are used for beers intended to be served using external gas cylinders.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Cask ales undergo part of their fermentation process in their containers, called casks.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Casks are available in several sizes, and it is common to refer to "a firkin" or "a kil" (kilderkin) instead of a cask.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The modern US beer barrel is 31 US gallons (117.34777 L), half a gallon less than the traditional wine barrel (26 U.S.C. §5051).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Barrels are also used as a unit of measurement for dry goods (dry groceries), such as flour or produce.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Traditionally, a barrel is 196 pounds (89 kg) of flour (wheat or rye), with other substances such as pork subject to more local variation.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] In modern times, produce barrels for all dry goods, excepting cranberries, contain 7,056 cubic inches, about 115.627 L.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] In the northeastern United States, nails, bolts, and plumbing fittings were commonly shipped in small rough barrels.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] These were small, 18 inches high by about 10–12 inches in diameter.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The wood was the quality of pallet lumber.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] The binding was sometimes by wire or metal hoops or both.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] This practice seems to have been prevalent up till the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/beer-barrel] Older hardware stores probably still have some of these barrels.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] In a piston engine, the **bore** (or **cylinder bore**) is the diameter of each cylinder.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] The stroke ratio, determined by dividing the bore by the stroke, traditionally indicated whether an engine was designed for power at high engine speeds (rpm) or torque at lower engine speeds.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] The term "bore" can also be applied to the bore of a locomotive cylinder or steam engine pistons.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] The term **bore** also applies to the cylinder of a steam locomotive or steam engine.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] The bore pitch is always larger than the inside diameter of the cylinder (the bore and piston diameter) since it includes the thickness of both cylinder walls and any water passage separating them.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] This is one of the first dimensions required when developing a new engine, since it limits maximum cylinder size (and therefore, indirectly, maximum displacement), and determines the length of the engine (L4, 6, 8) or of that bank of cylinders (V6, V8 etc.).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] In some older engines (such as the Chevrolet Gen-2 "Stovebolt" inline-six, the GMC straight-6 engine, the Buick Straight-eight, and the Chrysler "Slant 6") the bore pitch is additionally extended to allow more material between the main bearing webs in the block.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] For example, in an L6 the first pair (#1 & 2), center pair (#3 & 4), and rear pair (#5 & 6) of cylinders that share a pair of main bearings have a smaller pitch than between #2 & 3 and #4 & 5 that "bridge" a main bearing.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] Since the start-up expense of casting an engine block is very high, this is a strong incentive to retain this dimension for as long as possible to amortize the tooling cost over a large number of engines.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] If and when the engine is further refined, modified or enlarged, the bore pitch may be the only dimension retained from its predecessor.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] The bore diameter is frequently increased to the limit of minimal wall thickness, the water passage is eliminated between each pair of adjacent cylinders, the deck height is increased to accommodate a longer stroke, etc. but in general if the bore pitch is the same, the engines are related.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] All of these engines retain the original 4.460" bore pitch distance set down in 1956.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] "Hybrid" is the term commonly used to identify an engine modified for high performance by adapting a cylinder head from another (sometimes completely different) brand, size, model or type engine.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] Note: using a later head of the same engine "family" isn't a true hybrid, but mere modernization.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] In some cases, two heads from the donor (source) engine are joined end-to-end to match the number of cylinders on the subject engine (such as using three cylinders each of two V8 heads on a Chevrolet inline-six).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bore-engine] Identical or extremely similar bore pitch is what makes this possible, or (almost) impossible.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] The **Bristol 412** is a car which was produced by British manufacturer Bristol Cars from 1975 to 1986.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] Variants were produced as the **Bristol Beaufighter**, from 1980 to 1993, and as the **Bristol Beaufort**, from 1984 to 1994.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] Along with the Bristol 603, it was one of two concurrent successors to the long-serving 411 that had carried Bristol Cars through from the late 1960s to the mid 1970s.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] The 412 was the last in the continuously numbered series of Bristols beginning with Bristol 400.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] Whereas the 603 was a dramatically restyled version of the characteristic Bristol two-door saloon, the 412 was different in that it was a Targa-type convertible with a removable roof that could be placed in the large luggage compartment.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] The earliest versions of the 412 were also very unusual for a post-World War II car in that the body was made by Zagato in Italy and attached to a chassis built by Bristol Cars in Filton, England.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] This chassis was almost exactly the same as that of the Bristol 603, but the earliest 412s retained the Chrysler B series petrol engines 6.6 L (400 cu in) producing 264 bhp (197 kW) and 335 lb⋅ft (454 N⋅m) torque, that had been introduced in the 411 series 4 the previous year.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] The 1977 second series cars incorporated front suspension modifications to allow for the lighter engine, the LA engine was approximately 70 lb (32 kg) lighter than the previous B series engine, along with a final drive changed to the longer 2.88:1 ratio, to improve economy.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] Other changes included improved ventilation, redesigned seats, as fitted to the 603, and service intervals extended to 10,000 miles (16,000 km).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] In an effort to move into the United States market, Bristol designed a 412USA that complied with the extremely strict emissions and safety regulations of the US, with a catalytic converter and a much stronger roll bar than on the first 412.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] However, the company's specialist status made exporting very difficult and most of these modified 412 models were exported to Europe and markets such as West Germany and Switzerland.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] The Bristol Owners Club (BOC) website lists twenty-nine 412 series one cars, thirty-four 412 series two cars and two 412USA cars.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] The earliest cars had a fixed roof over the driver and passenger containing a glass sunroof.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] They also featured a new dashboard design.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] Later cars reverted to the lift out panel as per the 412, whilst retaining the glass sunroof and saw the dashboard design return to that used in the 412.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] The 5.9-litre V8 engine was upgraded by the addition of a Rotomaster turbocharger which increased power and torque by approximately 30%, giving the Beaufighter a maximum speed of 241 km/h (150 mph), limited by gearing, and a 0-60mph time of around 6 seconds.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] The Beaufighter was first built in 1980 and continued until 1993. “Fewer than 20” were made, according to the Bristol Cars website.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] The BOC website lists twenty eight (28) Beaufighter cars.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] For export only, primarily to continental Europe, the Beaufort, named after Bristol Aeroplane's Second World war torpedo bomber, the Bristol Beaufort, was the last development of the 412 to appear.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] It used the same turbocharged 5.9-litre V8 found in the Beaufighter.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] Unlike other versions of the 412, the Beaufort was a true convertible, with a powered roof.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] The Beaufort had a reinforced windscreen frame to compensate for the absence of a fixed roll bar.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] This allowed a range from one fill-up to the next of around 800 kilometres (500 mi) whereas the Britannia, Brigand, and Beaufighter could typically only go for 480 kilometres (300 mi) without refuelling.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] It was produced in very small numbers until 1994.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/bristol-412] The BOC website lists a single Beaufort as having been produced.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The **LA engine** is a family of overhead-valve small-block 90° V-configured gasoline engines built by Chrysler Corporation between 1964 and 2003.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Primarily V8s, the line includes a single V6 and V10, both derivations of its Magnum series introduced in 1992.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] A replacement of the Chrysler A engine, they were factory-installed in passenger vehicles, trucks and vans, commercial vehicles, marine and industrial applications.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Their combustion chambers are wedge-shaped, rather than polyspheric, as in the A engine, or hemispheric in the Chrysler Hemi.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] LA engines have the same 4.46 in (113 mm) bore spacing as the A engines.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] LA engines were made at Chrysler's Mound Road Engine plant in Detroit, Michigan, as well as plants in Canada and Mexico.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The "LA" stands for "Light A," as the 1956–1967 "A" engine it was closely based on and shares many parts with was nearly 50 pounds heavier.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The "LA" and "A" production overlapped from 1964–1966 in the U.S. and through 1967 in export vehicles when the "A" 318 engine was phased out.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The basic design of the LA engine would go unchanged through the development of the "Magnum" upgrade (1992–1993), and continue into the 2000s with changes to enhance power and efficiency.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The 238.2 cu in (3.9 L) V6 was introduced with the Dodge Dakota for 1987, and replaced the older, longer Slant-Six in the Dodge Ram trucks and vans for 1988.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] It is essentially a six-cylinder version of the 318 V8.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The bore and stroke are 99.3 mm (3.9 in) and 84 mm (3.3 in), respectively.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Output was 125 hp (93 kW) and 195 lb⋅ft (264 N⋅m) until it was replaced by the 3.9 L Magnum starting in 1992.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] In 1987, it used a two-barrel Holley carburetor and hydraulic valve lifters.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] In 1988, it was upgraded with throttle-body fuel injection and roller lifters.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] For the 1992 Magnum update, the throttle-body fuel injection was upgraded to a multi-port fuel injection system.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] In 1997, it was then upgraded to sequential fuel injection.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The engine was produced through 2003 before it was replaced with the 3.7 L PowerTech V6.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The 273 cu in (4.5 L) was the first LA engine, beginning model year 1964 and offered through 1969, rated at 180 hp (134 kW).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] It had a mechanical solid lifter valvetrain until 1968 when hydraulic lifters were introduced; hydraulic lifters generally make for a quieter valvetrain.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The reciprocating assembly included a cast or forged steel crankshaft, drop forged steel connecting rods and cast aluminum pistons.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The valvetrain consisted of a cast nodular iron camshaft, solid or hydraulic lifters, solid pushrods, and shaft-mounted, malleable iron rocker arms (stamped steel on later hydraulic-cam engines).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] These actuated the overhead steel intake and exhaust valves.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The cylinder heads featured wedge-shaped combustion chambers with a single intake and a single exhaust valve for each cylinder.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Spark plugs were located in the side of the cylinder head, between the exhaust ports.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] A high-performance 235 hp (175 kW) was offered from 1965 to 1967; called the "Commando", it was standard in the Barracuda Formula S model and optional in all other compact models excluding station wagons.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] It featured a 4-barrel carburetor and matching intake manifold, chrome unsilenced air cleaner with callout sticker, longer-duration and higher-lift camshaft and stronger valve springs, 10.5:1 compression ratio, and special black wrinkle valve covers with extruded aluminum appliqués.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] It was fitted to a low-restriction exhaust system with a 2.5 in (64 mm) exhaust pipe, collector-type Y-junction, and exposed resonator.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] For 1965 (only), the muffler was of "straight through" construction.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] A special version, exclusive to the 1966 Dodge Dart, was available.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] It used a 0.5 in (12.7 mm) lift solid-lifter camshaft, fabricated-steel-tube exhaust, and a Holley 4-barrel carburetor, producing 275 hp (205 kW) (1 hp/cu in).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The car so equipped was called the "D-Dart," a reference to its classification in NHRA D-stock for drag racing, which was the car's only intended purpose.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] It appeared in volume production beginning with the 1968 model year, replacing the last of the export "A" 318 engines equipped with polyspherical chambered heads ("A" 318 engines were not offered in 1967 domestic vehicles).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The LA engine was available until 1991, when it was superseded by the Magnum version.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] It used hydraulic lifters and a two-barrel carburetor for most of its production, though four-barrel Carter Thermo-Quad and Rochester Quadrajet carburetors were used in police applications starting in 1978 and 1985, respectively.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The 318 two-barrel ELD received roller lifters and a fast-burn chambered cylinder head in 1985 (the four-barrel police ELE 318 continued to use modified J heads and hydraulic flat valve lifters through 1989).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Throttle-body electronic fuel injection was factory equipment on the 1981–1983 Imperial.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] From 1988 to 1991, another throttle-body fuel injection system was used for truck and van applications.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] In the mid-1960s, Chrysler decided to adapt the 318 cu in (5.2 L) small block V8 into a lightweight, high output engine equally suited for drag strip or street performance use.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Its block was bored out to 4.04 in (102.6 mm) but its 3.31 in (84.1 mm) stroke left unchanged, resulting in the 340 cu in (5.6 L) engine introduced for the 1968 model year.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Anticipating higher loads resulting from racing operation, the engineers fitted a forged shot peened steel crankshaft instead of the cast steel unit used in the 318.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] This also included shot peened hammer-forged steel connecting rods and high compression cast aluminum pistons with full floating pins.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] A 4-barrel carburetor was mated to a high-rise, dual plane intake manifold feeding high-flow cylinder heads that are still considered among the best of that era.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Its big ports used 2.02 in (51 mm) intake and 1.60 in (41 mm) exhaust valves.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] An aggressive cam was fitted to take advantage of the much better breathing top end.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The 1968 4-speed cars got an even hotter cam, but it was discontinued for 1969, where both automatic and manual cars shared the same cam.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The engine was equipped with hydraulic lifters and two bolt main bearing caps, leading some to initially underestimate the 340's potential.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The 1968–71 340's compression ratio was 10.5:1, placing it near the limit of what was possible on pump gasoline during that era.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The 340 also used additional heavy-duty parts, such as a double-row roller timing chain and sump-mounted windage tray.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Power output was officially stated as 275 hp (205 kW) gross for the 4 barrel.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] In 1970, Chrysler introduced a special triple carburetor version of the 340 with triple 2-barrels at 290 hp (216 kW) gross.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Exclusively called the catchy **Six-Pack** on the Trans-Am targeted Dodge Challenger TA models, the same configuration was used by Plymouth for its Trans-Am AAR 'Cuda, called just the "340-6" or "six barrel".
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] This race-oriented version of the already high-performance 340 featured an aluminum intake manifold mounting three Holley carburetors, a dual points ignition system, and a heavy duty short block with additional webbing to allow for aftermarket installed 4 bolt main bearing caps.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The application-specific cylinder heads featured relocated intake pushrod passages with offset rocker arms that allowed the pushrods to be moved away from the intake ports, which could improve airflow if the pushrod-clearance "hump" was ground away from the intake port by the end user.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] For the 1974 model year, it was replaced by the 360 cu in (5.9 L) engine.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] It was released in 1971 with a two-barrel carburetor.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The 360 used the large intake port 340 heads with a smaller intake valve of 1.88 in (48 mm).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] In 1974, with the introduction of the code E58 4-barrel dual-exhaust version, at 245 hp (183 kW) SAE net, it became the most powerful LA engine with the end of 340 production.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Power started dropping from 1975 on as more emission controls were added resulting with the 1980 E58 engine only producing 185 hp (138 kW) SAE net.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Starting with 1981, the 360 was exclusively used in Dodge trucks and vans.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Some prototypes for the EH1 featured Mopar Performance W2 heads, although the production units had the standard 360 heads.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Some police package cars came from the factory with a steel crank and h-beam rods.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] There was also a "lean burn" version of the 360.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The LA360 was replaced in 1993 by the 5.9 Magnum, which shared some design parameters with the LA360, but the majority of its components were different.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Due to additional modifications, the prototype Li'l Red Express truck tested by various period magazines ran appreciably stronger than actual production examples.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The last variation of the LA series to be introduced before the Magnum upgrade was the 1988–92 throttle-body fuel injected, roller cam engine.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The first engines to receive these modifications were the 318 cu in (5.2 L) V8 and 239 cu in (3.9 L) V6 engines.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] A Holley/Chrysler-designed, single-point, twin-injector throttle body assembly was mounted atop a slightly redesigned cast iron intake manifold.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] An in-tank electric pump and reservoir replaced the earlier mechanical (camshaft-eccentric driven) pump.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The valvetrain was upgraded to include hydraulic roller lifters; however, cam specifications remained essentially unchanged.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The resulting engine was somewhat improved as to power and efficiency.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The 5.9 L V8 engines followed suit in 1989, but also received the overall improved "308" cylinder heads (casting number 4448308) that featured significantly higher flowing exhaust ports and a return to the original 1971 (non-fast burn) combustion chamber.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] However, with other manufacturers already introducing the superior multi-point fuel injection system, Chrysler considered a more drastic upgrade program.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] As the TBI engines were being introduced, the new upgrade program was initiated in the Chrysler engineering department.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] In 1992, with emissions standards becoming ever more stringent in the United States, Chrysler Corporation released the first of the upgraded engines.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] In 1992, Chrysler introduced the first of a series of upgraded versions of the LA engines.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The company named their engine the "Magnum," a marketing term that had been used by the company previously to describe both the Dodge Magnum automobile and an earlier Dodge passenger car (only) engine series; the latter was based on the big-block B/RB V8 engines of the 1960s–70s.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The Chrysler Magnum engines are a series of V6, V8, and V10 powerplants used in a number of Chrysler Corporation motor vehicles, as well as in marine and industrial applications.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] This family of gasoline-burning engines lasted for over a decade, were installed in vehicles sold across the globe, and were produced in the millions.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The Magnum engine is a direct descendant of the Chrysler LA engine, which began with the 273 cu in (4.5 L) V8 in 1964.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The cylinder block remained basically the same.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] It was still a V-shaped, 90-degree design made of cast iron.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The crankshaft, located to the bottom of the block by five main bearing caps, was cast steel, and the eight connecting rods were forged steel.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The pistons were cast aluminum, with a hypereutectic design.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Cylinders were numbered from the front of the engine to the rear; cylinders 1, 3, 5, and 7 were found on the left (driver side) bank, or "bank 1," with the even numbers on the other bank.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Coolant passages were located between the cylinders.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The gerotor-type oil pump was located at the bottom-rear of the engine, and provided oil to both the crankshaft main bearings and the cylinder heads (via the lifters and pushrods, as opposed to a bored passage on LA engines).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Chrysler's engineers also redesigned the oil seals on the crankshaft to improve anti-leak seal performance.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The oil pan was also made from thicker steel, and was installed with a more leak-resistant silicone-rubber gasket.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Gasoline was supplied to the intake manifold through a pair of steel rails that fed eight Bosch-type, top-fed, electronically actuated fuel injectors; there was one injector located in each intake runner.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Each cylinder had its own injector, thus making the fuel system a "multi-point" type.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Fuel pressure was regulated by a vacuum-controlled pressure regulator, located on the return side of the second fuel rail.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Excess fuel was thereafter delivered back to the fuel tank.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] To support the new fuel system, the intake manifold was of a new design.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Known colloquially as the "beer keg" or "kegger" manifold, the part was shaped like half of a beer barrel lying longitudinally atop the center of the V-shaped engine block.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The intake runners, which supplied the fuel and air to each cylinder, fed each of the intake ports in the newly designed cylinder heads.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The bolts that secured the intake manifold to the cylinder heads were installed at a different angle from those on the older LA engine; they threaded in vertically, rather than at the 45-degree angle of the 1966 and up LA.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Air was provided from the air filter intake to the intake manifold by a Holley-designed, aluminum, twin-venturi, mechanically actuated throttle body, which was bolted atop the intake manifold.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Each venturi was progressively bored and had a diameter of 50mm.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] To this unit were mounted the Throttle Position Sensor (TPS), Manifold Absolute Pressure (MAP) sensor and Idle Air Control (IAC) valve (initially referred to as the "AIS Motor").
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] A steel cable connected the accelerator pedal inside the vehicle to a mechanical linkage at the side of the throttle body, which acted to open the air intake butterfly valves inside the venturis.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] During idle these butterfly valves were closed, so a bypass port and the IAC valve were used to control the intake of air.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The cylinder heads were another fundamental change of the Magnum engine, being designed to meet stricter requirements in both power and emissions by increasing efficiency.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] These heads were cast iron units with new wedge-shaped combustion chambers and high-swirl valve shrouding.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Combustion chamber design was most important in these new heads: LA engine cylinder heads were given a full-relief open-chamber design, but the Magnum was engineered with a double-quench closed-chamber type.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The higher-flowing intake ports stepped up intake flow dramatically in comparison to the original LA heads, and the exhaust ports improved cylinder evacuation as well.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The shape and porting of the chambers allowed for more complete atomization of the air/fuel mixture, as well as contributing to more complete combustion; these virtues allowed for much greater efficiency of the engine as a whole.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The intake and exhaust valves were located at the top of each combustion chamber.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The valves themselves had shorter, 5/16" diameter stems, to allow for the more aggressive camshaft.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Intake valves had a port diameter of 1.92", while exhaust valves were 1.600", with 60cc combustion chambers.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Spark plugs were located at the peak of the combustion chambers' wedge, between the exhaust ports; press-in heat shields protected them from the heat of the exhaust manifolds.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Cast iron exhaust manifolds, less restrictive than units found on previous engines, were bolted to the outboard side of each head.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The new cylinder heads also featured stud-mounted rocker arms, a change from the shaft-mounted LA arms.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] This last change was due to the different oiling system of the new engine, as described in the next paragraph.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The valve covers on the Magnum have 10 bolts rather than the previous 5, for improved oil sealing.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] In addition, the valve covers were made of thicker steel than earlier parts, and were installed with a silicone gasket.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The valvetrain was also updated, although it was still based on a single, center-block located camshaft pushing on hydraulic lifters and pushrods, one for each rocker arm.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] However, the cast nodular iron camshaft was of the "roller" type, with each lobe acting upon a hydraulic lifter with a roller bearing on the bottom; this made for a quieter, cooler-running valvetrain, but also allowed for a more aggressive valve lift.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Each of the lifters acted upon a steel pushrod, which were of the "oil-through" type.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Because the new pushrods also served to provide oil to the top of the cylinder head, the rockers were changed to the AMC-style, screw-mounted, bridged half-shaft type.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The new rockers also had a higher ratio: 1.6:1 compared to 1.5:1 in the LA engine, which increased leverage on the valves.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] In addition, the oil boss located at the end of the cylinder head on the LA engine was left undrilled, as it was no longer needed.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] However, the boss itself was left in place, perhaps to cut down on casting and machining costs, and to allow the use of earlier LA heads.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Engine timing was controlled by the all-steel, silent Morse timing chain (some early production engines had double-row roller timing sets), which was located beneath the aluminum timing cover at the front of the engine block.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The timing chain sprockets, one each for the camshaft and crankshaft, were all-steel; for the last few years, the LA engine came with nylon teeth on the sprockets.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] At the rear of the camshaft was cut a set of helical gear teeth, these being used to spin the distributor.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Mounted to the front of the timing cover was a redesigned, counterclockwise rotation water pump, with much improved flow.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Externally, the accessory drive belt was changed to a serpentine system; coupled with an automatic belt tensioner this increased belt life, reduced maintenance and contributed to lower noise and vibration levels.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The ignition system was also all-new for the Magnum.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Controlled by a new micro-processor-equipped Single-Board Engine Controller (SBEC, also known as the ECM, or Engine Control Module), the ignition system included a distributor mounted at the rear of the engine.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] A 36,000-volt ignition coil, usually located at the front right of the engine, provided electrical power to the center of the distributor cap, where a spinning rotor directed the power to each of the individual cylinders' spark plug wires.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Ignition dwell, advance and retardation were electronically controlled by the SBEC.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The SBEC controlled the ignition, as well as the opening and closing of the fuel injectors.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] During cold startup, wide-open throttle and deceleration, it did this based on "open-loop," pre-programmed operating parameters.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] During normal idle and cruising, it began "closed-loop" operation, during which the module acted based upon inputs from a variety of sensors.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The basic sensors that provided input to the SBEC included the Oxygen sensor (O2), Manifold Absolute Pressure (MAP) sensor, Throttle Position Sensor (TPS), Intake Air Temperature (IAT) sensor and Coolant Temperature sensor (CTS).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The basic actuators controlled by the SBEC's outputs included the fuel injectors, ignition coil and pickup, and the Idle Air Control (IAC) valve.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The latter controlled idle characteristics.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] However, the SBEC also controlled the operation of the charging system, air conditioning system, cruise control and, in some vehicles, transmission shifting.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] By centralizing control of these systems, the operation of the vehicle was simplified and streamlined.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Emissions output was controlled by several systems.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The EGR, or Exhaust Gas Recirculation system, brought exhaust gas from the exhaust stream up to the intake manifold, lowering peak combustion temperatures, the goal being the reduction of NOX emissions.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] A PCV, or Positive Crankcase Ventilation system, introduced oil vapor and unburnt fuel vapors from the crankcase to the intake, allowing the engine to re-use these as well.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Furthermore, gasoline vapors that would normally be released into the atmosphere were captured by the EVAP system, to then be introduced into the engine.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] In 1996, the OBD-II on-board diagnostics system was introduced on all passenger vehicles in the United States, as per United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) regulation.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] As such, a new engine control computer was developed for vehicles powered by Magnum engines, known as the JTEC.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The new Powertrain Control Module was more complex and more intelligent, and added programming meant it could also control automatic transmission and other powertrain functions; its firmware could also be reprogrammed ("reflashed") via the same OBD-II port.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] With the introduction of the JTEC, the EGR system was dropped from Magnum engines.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] As the 5.2 L V8 was introduced in 1992, the often-forgotten V6 version of the Magnum engine became available in the Ram pickup and the more compact Dodge Dakota.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Based on the LA-series 239 cu in (3.9 L) V6, the 3.9 L Magnum featured the same changes and upgrades as the other Magnum engines.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The 3.9 L is essentially a 5.2 L V8 with two cylinders removed.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Power increased substantially to 180 hp (134 kW) at 4,400 rpm and from 195 to 220 lb⋅ft (264 to 298 N⋅m) at 3,200 rpm, as compared with the previous TBI engine.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] For 1994, horsepower was reduced to 175 hp (130 kW), mostly because of the installation of smaller-volume exhaust manifolds; torque ratings remained the same.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] For 1997, the 3.9 L engine's torque output was increased to 225 lb⋅ft (305 N⋅m), with a compression ratio of 9.1:1.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] This engine was last produced for the 2003 Dodge Dakota pickup.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Starting in the 2004 model year, it was entirely withdrawn from production and replaced with the 3.7L PowerTech V6 engine.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The 5.2 L Magnum, released in 1992, was an evolutionary development of the 318 cu in (5.2 L) LA engine with the same displacement.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The 5.2 L was the first of the Magnum upgraded engines, followed in 1993 by the 5.9 L V8 and the 3.9 L V6.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] At the time of its introduction, the 5.2 L Magnum created 230 hp (172 kW) at 4,100 rpm and 295 lb⋅ft (400 N⋅m) at 3,000 rpm.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Production of this engine lasted until 2003, when it was completely replaced by the newer 4.7 L PowerTech SOHC V8 engine.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] In 1993, Chrysler Corporation released the next member of the Magnum family: the 5.9 L V8.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] This was based on the LA-series 360 cu in (5.9 L) engine, and included the same upgrades and design features as the 5.2 L.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The standard 5.9 L produced 230 hp (172 kW) at 4,000 rpm and 325 lb⋅ft (441 N⋅m) at 3,200 rpm; torque was increased to 330 lb⋅ft (447 N⋅m) at 2,800 rpm in the heavy-duty version.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The 5.9 L came factory-installed in 1998–2001 Dodge Dakota R/T pickups and 2000–2003 Dodge Durango R/T SUVs.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] It was also installed in the Jeep Grand Cherokee Limited 5.9, only available in 1998.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The 5.9 L Magnum was available until the 2003 model year, when it was replaced with the 5.7 L Hemi V8 engine.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Although the pre-Magnum (1971–92) and Magnum versions of the 360 cu in (5.9 L) are both externally balanced, the two are balanced differently (the Magnum version uses lighter pistons) and each requires a uniquely balanced damper, flywheel, drive plate, or torque converter.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Bore and stroke size was 4 in × 3.58 in (101.6 mm × 90.9 mm); compression ratio was 9.1:1.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The Magnum V10 was a 488 cu in (8.0 L) V10 engine designed for use in Dodge Ram 2500 and 3500 trucks, which made its debut in 1994 and was produced through 2003.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Although Chrysler had already introduced an aluminum block Lamborghini-influenced V10 in the 1991 Dodge Viper, this engine's roots trace to the genesis of the 5.2 L Magnum V8 in 1988.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Valve covers were die-cast magnesium (AZ91D alloy), rather than stamped steel; this lowered noise levels and made for better gasket sealing.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] The Magnum V10 first became available in the 1994 model year Dodge Ram 2500 and 3500 (above 8,500 pounds GVWR), and was the most powerful gasoline-burning engine then available in any truck of that class.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Chrysler has offered a line of crate engines based on the Magnum designed to bolt into older muscle cars and street rods with little modification.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Some of the changes to facilitate this were using a 1970–93 coolant pump so that older pulleys and brackets could be used, as well as an intake manifold that uses a carburetor instead of electronic fuel injection.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] With a high lift cam and single plane intake, the crate Magnum 360 cu in (5.9 L) was rated at 380 hp (283 kW) with the Magnum heads.
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] Later models equipped with "R/T" or aluminum cylinder heads produced 390 hp (291 kW).
[src:chrysler-la-engine/chrysler-la-engine] A 425 hp (317 kW) bolt-in fuel injection conversion kit has also been available.
